Introduction

In the last sections, we discussed how we can estimate genetic parameters and predict genetic values. Using this information, the breeder not only has practical tools to perform selection but also provides the theoretical basis for monitoring the genetic progress in a given population. While artificial selection changes the array of gene frequencies and therefore modifies the mean performance of a population, it is the knowledge of the heritability that will allow us predicting the phenotypic performance in the next generations. Given the important, we introduce the breederâs equation. Just based on its name, we can recognize its importance in the routine of any breeding program.

Theory

Breederâs equation

The heritability provides the basis for predicting the outcome of selection on quantitative traits according to:

\[R = h^2S\]

where R is the response to selection, \(h^2\) is the narrow-sense heritability, and S is the selection differential that measures the strength of selection. Let S be the mean phenotypic value of the selected parents, expressed as a deviation from the population. Thus, the response to selection is the chage in the population mean due to selection. This value predicted by the breederâs equation is intuitive. Stronger selection or phenotypic variation that has a greater basis in additive genetic variance will result in a greater change in the mean phenotype in a population.

Bellow, a hypothetical example of directional selection and response to selection from Hamilton (2009). Check the the lower bound of phenotypic values in the group of parents selected to mate and how the selection differencial is computed as the difference bettwen the phenotypic mean of the selected parents and the phenotypic mean of the entire population. As a connection with the theory, selection differentials can be expressed in units of standard deviations by standardizing phenotypic values in the parental population to have a mean of zero and a variance of one. Finally, check how the population means shifted toward the mean of the selected individuals.

Example of response to selection from Hamilton (2009)

Intensity of selection

Assuming that a trait is normally distributed and selection is by truncation â individuals are chosen strictly in order of merits as judged by their phenotypic values â selection differencial depends of two main factors:

  • Proportion of individuals selected for the next generation.
  • Variability presented in the original population expressed as phenotypic standard deviation of the trait.

The standardized selection differential, usually called the selection intensity (i) is the selection differential expressed as a fraction of the phenotypic standard deviation (\(\frac{S}{\sigma^2_p}\)). The standard deviation provides a common scale unit, which is particularly handy when comparing different traits, or when dealing with several traits at the same time. Thus, we can rearrange the breederâs equation in the following format:

\[R=ih^2\sigma^2_p\]

\[R=ih\sigma^2_a\]

In short, the gain that can be obtained by selection in a given population is therefore a function of the amount of variation present (\(\sigma^2_a\)), how much of this variation is genetic (h), and how intensively one selects in this population (i). It is often convenient to express the expected gain in terms of a percent.

The breedersâ equation thus far calculates response to selection per generation. However, to calculate the selection response per year, the generation interval is required. A similar way to represent the equation is \(R=\frac{ih^2\sigma^2_p}{L}\), where L is the generation interval or breeding cycle.

Improving the response

Breeders might improve the rate of genetic gains using different strategies:

  • Although \(h^2\) is a property of the population, we know that increasing the number of repetitions and reducing the experimental error (\(\sigma^2_e\)) has an influence on the \(h^2\) estimation. Simply stating, proper experimental designs and good field practices can positively affect the \(h^2\) estimation and hence the genetic gains.
  • Increasing the intensity of selection appears to be the first option to improve the response. However, it can increase inbreeding and therefore reduce reproductive fitness. A harmonious balance between gain and diversity is an ideal scenario for most of the breeding programs.
  • Reduce the generation interval â here, there is an important argument to use molecular markers.

Hands on

In the simulation (originally reported here), we will explore how different parameters impact the response to selection and other measurements for a trait influenced by many genes. To this end, use the Response to Selection link.

By using the app we can use the following logic:

  • By focusing on the \(h^2\) values: Using \(h^2=0\), \(i=0.2\), \(p=0.5\) and \(N=2000\), what will happen with the genotypic value across the generations? Now, increase the \(h^2=0.5\) and \(h^2=1\).
  • What will happen with the genotypic value across the generations when we use a high selection intensity? And about the genetic variance and allele frequencies?
  • What will happen with the genotypic value and allele frequencies across the generations when we do not perform selection?

Conclusion

  • Breeders equation can be consider as the following product: Response = (Intensity) x (Accuracy in Predicting Breeding Value) x (Usable Variance)
  • In the sequence of this course we will address other factors that can also affect the genetic gains, including the use of selection index, correlated traits and, finally, marker-assisted selection via genomic prediction.
